//,. pm national ai strategy html version govuk introduction artificial intelligence technologies (al) offer the potential to transform the uk's economic landscape and improve people's lives across the country; transforming industries and delivering first-class services: al may be one of the most important innovations in human history, and the government believes it is critical to both our economic and national security that the uk prepares for the opportunities al brings, and that the country is at the forefront of solving the complex challenges posed by an increased use of ai. this country has a long and exceptional history in al  from alan turing's early work through to deepmind's recent pioneering discoveries. in terms of al startups and scaleups, private capital invested and conference papers submitted, the uk sits in the top tier of al nations globally: the uk ranked third in the world for private investment into al companies in , behind only the usa and china. the national al strategy builds on the uks current strengths and represents the start of a step-change for al in the uk, recognising that maximising the potential of al will increase resilience, productivity, growth and innovation across the private and sectors. building on our strengths in al will take a whole-of-society effort that will span the next decade. this is a top-level economic, security; health and wellbeing priority: the uk government sees being competitive in al as vital to our national ambitions on regional prosperity and for shared global challenges such as net zero, health resilience and environmental sustainability: al capability is therefore vital for the uk's international influence as a global science superpower the national al strategy for the united kingdom will prepare the uk for the next ten years, and is built on three assumptions about the coming decade: the key drivers of progress, discovery and strategic advantage in al are access to people, data, compute and finance ~ all of which face huge global competition; al will become mainstream in much of the economy and action will be required to ensure every sector and region of the uk benefit from this transition; our governance and regulatory regimes will need to keep pace with the fast- changing demands of ai, maximising growth and competition, driving uk excellence in innovation, and protecting the safety, security, choices and rights of our citizens. this document sets out the uk's strategic intent at a level intended to guide action over the next ten years, recognising that al is a fast moving and dynamic area. detailed and measurable plans for the execution of the first stage of this strategy will be published later this year:  www-gov.uk/government/publications/national-ai-strategy/national-ai-strategy-html-version / public public



//,. pm national ai strategy html version govuk the uks national artificial intelligence strategy will: invest and plan for the long term needs of the al ecosystem to continue our leadership as a science and al superpower;  support the transition to an al-enabled economy, capturing the benefits of innovation in the uk, and ensuring al benefits all sectors and regions;  ensure the uk gets the national and international governance of al technologies right to encourage innovation, investment;, and protect the and our fundamental values: this will be best achieved through broad public trust and support; and by the involvement of the diverse talents and views of society: -year vision over the next decade, as transformative technologies continue to reshape our economy and society, the world is likely to see a shift in the nature and distribution of global power: we are seeing how, in the case of al, rapid technological change seeks to rebalance the science and technology dominance of existing superpowers like the us and china, and wider transnational challenges demand greater collective action in the face of continued security and prosperity: with this in mind; the uk has an opportunity over the next ten years to position itself as the best place to live and work with al; with clear rules, applied ethical principles and a pro-innovation regulatory environment: with the right ingredients in place, we will be both a genuine innovation powerhouse and the most supportive business environment in the world; where we cooperate on using al for good, advocate for international standards that reflect our values, and defend against the malign use of ai. whether it is making the decision to study al, work at the cutting edge of research or spin up an al business; our investments in skills, data and infrastructure will make it easier than ever to succeed: our world-leading randd system will step up its support of innovators at every step of their journey; from deep research to building and shipping products if you are a talented al researcher from abroad,  www-gov.uk/government/publications/national-ai-strategy/national-ai-strategy-html-version / public global



//,. pm national ai html version govuk coming to the uk will be easier than ever through the array of visa routes which are available. if you run a business l whether it is a startup, sme or a large corporate the government wants you to have access to the people, knowledge and infrastructure you need to get your business ahead of the transformational change al will bring, making the uk a globally-competitive, al-first economy which benefits every region and sector by leading with our democratic values, the uk will work with partners around the world to make sure international agreements embed our ethical values, making clear that progress in al must be achieved responsibly, according to democratic norms and the rule of law: and by increasing the number and diversity of people working with and developing al, by putting clear rules of the road in place and by investing across the entire country; we will ensure the real-world benefits of al are felt by every member of society: whether that is more accurate al-enabled diagnostics in the nhs, the promise of driverless cars to make our roads safer and smarter; or the hundreds of unforeseen benefits that al could bring to improve everyday life. the goals of this strategy are that the uk: experiences a significant growth in both the number and type of discoveries that happen in the uk, and are commercialised and exploited here;  benefits from the highest amount of economic and productivity growth due to al; and establishes the most trusted and pro-innovation system for al governance in the world. this vision can be achieved if we build on three pillars fundamental to the development of al:  www-gov.uk/government/publications/national-ai-strategy/national-ai-strategy-html-version / strategy



//,. pm national ai strategy html version govuk investing in the needs of the ecosystem to see more people working with al, more access to data and compute resources to train and deliver al systems; and access to finance and customers to grow sectors;  supporting the diffusion of al across the whole economy to ensure all regions, nations, businesses and sectors can benefit from and  developing a pro-innovation regulatory and governance framework that protects the public the national al strategy does not stand alone it purposefully supports and amplifies the other; interconnected work of government including: the plan for growth ( /iwww gov uklgovernmentlpublicationsbbuild-back-better_ our-plan-for-growth) and recent innovation strategy ( iiww 9ov_uklgovernment/publicationsluk-innovation-strategy-leading-the-future_ by-creating-it), which recognise the need to develop a diverse and inclusive pipeline of al professionals with the capacity to supercharge innovation; the integrated review ( iiwww gov uklgovernmentlpublications/global-britain-in_ a-competitive-age-the-integrated-review-of-security-defence-development-and-foreign- policy) to find new paths for uk excellence in al to deliver prosperity and security at home and abroad, and shape the open international order of the future; the national data strategy_( iiwww gov uklgovernmentlpublications/uk national-data-strategy), published in september , sets out our vision to harness the power of responsible data use to boost productivity, create new businesses and jobs, improve public services, support a fairer society, and drive scientific discovery; positioning the uk as the forerunner of the next wave of innovation; the plan for digital regulation ( iiwww gov uklgovernmentlpublications/digital- regulation-driving-growth-and-unlocking-innovation) which sets out our pro- innovation approach to regulating digital technologies in a way that drives prosperity and builds trust in their use; the upcoming national cyber strategy to continue the drive for securing emerging technologies, including building security into the development of ai; the forthcoming digital strategy; which will build on dcms's ten_tech priorities ( iidcms shorthandstories com/qur-ten-tech-prioritieslindex html) to further set out the government's ambitions in the digital sector;  new defence al centre as a keystone of the modernisation of defence;  www-gov.uk/government/publications/national-ai-strategy/national-ai-strategy-html-version / ai; piece



//,. pm national ai strategy html version govuk the national security technology innovation exchange (nstix) , a data science and al co-creation space that brings together national security stakeholders; industry and academic partners to build better national security capabilities; and the upcoming national resilience strategy ( :iiwwgov uklgovernment/consultationsinational-resilience-strategy-call-for- evidence), which will in part focus on how the uk will stay on top of technological threats. the government's al council ( i www gov uklgovernmentlgroupslai-council) has played a central role in gathering evidence to inform the development of this strategy; including through its roadmap ( iiwww gov uklgovernmentlpublicationslai- roadmap) published at the beginning of the year; which represents a valuable set of recommendations reflecting much of the wider al community in the uk. the wider ecosystem also fed in through a survey ( iiwww turing_ac uklai-ecosystem-survey_ summary-report) run by the al council in collaboration with the alan turing institute. the government remains grateful to the al council for its continued leadership of the al ecosystem, and would like to thank those from across the united kingdom who shared their views during the course of developing this strategy: the al council the al council was established in  to provide expert advice to the government and high-level leadership of the al ecosystem. the al council demonstrates a key commitment made in the al sector deal, bringing together respected leaders in their fields from across industry; academia and the public sector: members meet quarterly to advise the office for al and broader government on its current priorities, opportunities and challenges for al policy: in january , the al council published its al roadmap' providing  recommendations to the government on the strategic direction for al. its central call was for the government to develop a national al strategy; building on the success of investments made through the al sector deal whilst remaining adaptable to future technological disruption: since then, the council has led a programme of engagement with the wider al community to inform the development of the national al strategy: to the delivery and implementation of this strategy the government will renew and strengthen the role of the al council, ensuring it continues to provide expert advice to government and high-level leadership of the al ecosystem:  www-gov.uk/government/publications/national-ai-strategy/national-ai-strategy-html-version / guide



//,. pm national ai html version govuk al presents unique opportunities and challenges 'artificial intelligence as a term can mean a lot of things, and the government recognises that no single definition is going to be suitable for every scenario. in general, the following definition is sufficient for our purposes: "machines that perform tasks normally performed by human intelligence , especially when the machines learn from data how t0 do those tasks. the uk government has also set out a legal definition of al in the national security and investment act [footnote ] much like james watt's  steam engine, al is a 'general purpose technology (or more accurately, technologies) that have many possible applications, and we expect them to have a transformational impact on the whole economy: already, al is used in everyday contexts like email spam filtering; media recommendation systems, navigation apps, payment transaction validation and verification, and many more. ai technologies will impact the whole economy, all of society and us as individuals: many of the themes in al policy are similar to tech and digital policy more widely: the commercialisation journeys; the reliance on internationally mobile talent; the importance of data; and consolidation of economic functions onto platforms however there are some key examples of differences derived from the above definition which differentiate al and require a unique policy response from the government: in regulatory matters, a system's autonomy raises unique questions around liability, assurance, and fairness as well as risk and safety and even ownership of creative contentifootnote ] in a way which is distinct to al, and these questions increase with the relative complexity of the algorithm. there are also questions of transparency and bias which arise from decisions made by ai systems. there are often greater infrastructure requirements for al services than in cloud/software as a service systems. in building and deploying some models, access to expensive high performance computing andlor large data sets is needed: multiple skills are required to develop, validate and deploy al systems, and the commercialisation and product journey can be longer and more expensive because so much starts with fundamental randd: reflecting and protecting society al makes predictions and decisions, and fulfils tasks normally undertaken by humans while diverse opinions, skills, backgrounds and experience are hugely  www-govuklgovernment/publications/national-ai-strategy/national-ai-strategy-html-version / strategy



//,. pm national ai strategy html version govuk important in designing any service digital or otherwise s it is particularly important in al because of the executive function of the systems. as al increasingly becomes an enabler for transforming the economy and our personal lives, there are at least three reasons we should care about diversity in our al ecosystem: moral: as al becomes an organising principle which creates new opportunities and changes the shape of industries and the dynamics of competition across the economy; there is a moral imperative to ensure people from all backgrounds and parts of the uk are able to participate and thrive in this new al economy: social: al systems make decisions based on the data they have been trained on. if that data or the system it is embedded in  is not representative, it risks perpetuating or even cementing new forms of bias in society: it is therefore important that people from diverse backgrounds are included in the development and deployment of al systems: economic: there are big economic benefits to a diverse al ecosystem: these include increasing the uks human capital from a diverse labour supply, creating a wider range of al services that stimulate demand, and ensuring the best talent is discovered from the most diverse talent pool. the longer term making specific predictions about the future impact of a technology f as opposed to the needs of those developing and using it today has a long history in ai. since the 1950s various hype cycles have given to so-called al winters' as the promises made have perpetually remained 'about  years away' . while the emergence of artificial general intelligence (agi) may seem like a science fiction concept; concern about al safety and non-human-aligned systemsffootnote ] is by no means restricted to the fringes of the field [footnote ] the government's first focus is on the economic and social outcomes of autonomous and adaptive systems that exist today: however; we take the firm stance that it is critical to watch the evolution of the technology, to take seriously the possibility of agi and 'more general al' , and to actively direct the technology in a peaceful; human-aligned direction [fooinote ] the emergence of full agi would have a transformational impact on almost every aspect of life, but there are many challenges which could be presented by al which could emerge much sooner than this. as a general purpose technology al will have economic and social impacts comparable to the combustion engine, the car; the computer and the internet: as each of these has disrupted and changed  www-gov.uk/government/publications/national-ai-strategy/national-ai-strategy-html-version / way



//,. pm national ai html version govuk the shape of the world we live in so too could al, long before any system 'wakes up. the choices that are made in the here and now to develop al will shape the future of humanity and the course of international affairs. for example, whether al is used to enhance peace, or a cause for war; whether al is used to strengthen our democracies, or embolden authoritarian regimes. as such we have a responsibility to not only look at the extreme risks that could be made real with agi, but also to consider the dual-use threats we are already faced with today: from sector deal to al strategy the uk is an al superpower; with particular strengths in research, investment and innovation. the uk's academic and commercial institutions are well known for conducting world-leading al research, and the uk ranks 3rd in the world for ai publication citations per capita [footnote z] this research strength was most recently demonstrated in november  when deepmind ( iideepmind com/), a uk- based al company, used alphafold to find a solution to a -year-old grand challenge in biology [footnote ] the uk has the 3rd highest number of al companies in the world after the us and china: alongside deepmind, the uk is home to graphcore ( iiwww_graphcore ail), a bristol-based machine learning semiconductor company; darktrace_( iiwww darktrace com/en/), a world-leading al company for cybersecurity; and benevolental ( iiwwwbenevolent coml, a company changing the way we treat disease. the uk also attracts some of the best al talent from around the worldlfootnote ] the uk was the second most likely global destination for mobile al researchers after the usa. alphafold and alphafold  in november , london-based deepmind announced that they had solved one of the longest running modern challenges in biology: predicting how proteins the building blocks of life which underpin every biological process in every living thing take shape, or 'fold' .  www-gov.uk/government/publications/national-ai-strategy/national-ai-strategy-html-version / strategy



