//,. pm national ai html version govuk the government has invested more than e2. billion into artificial intelligence across a range of initiatives since .[footnote ] this portfolio of investment includes, but is not limited to: e250 million to develop the nhs al lab at nhsx to accelerate the safe adoption of artificial intelligence in health and care; e250 million into connected and autonomous mobility (cam) technology through the centre for connected and autonomous vehicles (ccav) to develop the future of mobility in the uk;  new al centres for doctoral training at universities across the country; backed by up to  million and delivering , new phds over five years; anew industry-funded al masters programme and up to , places for al and data science conversion courses this includes up to , government-funded scholarships; investment into the alan turing institute and over e46 million to support the turing al fellowships to develop the next generation of top al talent; over e372 million of investment into uk al companies through the british business bank for the growing al sector; e172 million of investment through the ukri into the hartree national centre for digital innovation, leveraging an additional  million of private investment into high performance computing: further investments have been made into the tech nation applied alprogramme ( iltechnation iolprogrammeslapplied-ai = now in its third iteration; establishing the office for national statistics data science campus ( iidatasciencecampusonsgov uk); the crown commercial service's public sector al procurement portal ( iiwww crowncommercial gov uklagreements/rm62oo); and support for the department for international trade attracting al related foreign direct investment into the uk as part of the al sector deal, the government established the al council to bring together respected leaders to strengthen the conversation between academia, industry; and the public sector: the office for artificial intelligence ( iiwww govuklgovernmentlorganisations/office-for-artificial-intelligence) was created as a new team within government to take responsibility for overarching al policy across government and to be a focal for the al ecosystem through its secretariat of the al council the centre_for data ethics and innovation ( iiwww gov uklgovernmentlorganisations/centre-for-data-ethics-and-innovation) (cdei) was established as a government expert body focused on the trustworthy use of data and al in the public and private sector: this strategy builds on the recent history of government support for al and considers the next key steps to harness its potential in the uk for the coming  www-gov.uk/government/publications/national-ai-strategy/national-ai-strategy-html-version / strategy point



//,. pm national ai html version govuk decade. in doing so, the national al strategy leads on from the ambitions outlined in the governments innovation strategy ( iiwwwgov uklgovernmentlpublications/uk-innovation-strategy-leading-the-future-by_ creating-it) to enable uk businesses and innovators to respond to economic opportunities and real-world problems through our national innovation prowess. al was identified in the innovation strategy as one of the seven technology families where the uk has a globally competitive randd and industrial strengthlfootnote ] and has been widely cited as a set of technologies in which the uk must maintain a leading edge to guarantee our continued security and prosperity in an intensifying geopolitical landscape. pillar : investing in the long-term needs of the al ecosystem investingin the long- term needs of the ai ecosystem investing in and planning for the long term needs of the al ecosystem to remain a science and al superpower to maintain the uks position amongst the global al superpowers and ensure the uk continues to lead in the research, development, commercialisation and  / strategy



